data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider let you opt into **sync-over-async** behavior (e.g., via `EnableSyncOverAsync()`). In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), **that opt-in is removed entirely**.

Every synchronous LINQ call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()` — and `SaveChanges()` will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime because the Cosmos SDK is async-only and EF Core no longer wraps it.

## The fix: go fully async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return `Task<T>` / `Task`, mark methods `async`
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Rename methods with `Async` suffix (convention)

All callers up the chain must be updated to `await` these methods. This typically propagates up through services and controllers ("async all the way").
